5","1320":"1320","Aft 1360":"after 1360","after 10 January 1363":"after 10 January 1363","Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland":"Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland","Lovat Castle, Beauly, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bissett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>biset</i> ‘dark’, a diminutive of <i>bis</i> (see   Biss  ).","Altered form of French <b>Bizet</b>: nickname for someone with a dark complexion, derived from <i>bis</i> ‘grayish-brown’. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Bissette  .","History: The surname <i>Bissett</i> (see 1 above) was brought to Scotland from Nottinghamshire <i>c.</i> 1175 by Henricus Byset, an Englishman who became a retainer of King William the Lion. — It was Jean George Bizet from Haute-Saône, France, whose surname was changed to <i>Bissett</i> (see 2 above) after his immigration to NS, Canada, in 1752."],"variants":[{"name":"Biss","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bis</i> ‘brownish or dark gray’ (Old French <i>bis</i>), denoting someone with a dark complexion or who wore dark clothing.","South German: nickname for a cutting, sarcastic person, from <i>Biss</i> ‘bite’."]},{"name":"Bissette","meanings":["American French: variant of   Bissett  ."]},{"name":"Bisset","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Bissett  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bisse</i> ‘fine linen’ (see   Bisson  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bissett was born about 1327, in Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland, his father, Thomas Bisset, was 38 and his mother, Anne Bradburn, was 36. He married Isabella MacDuff after 10 January 1363, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 17 April 1365, in Fife, Scotland, at the age of 39."},"et":{"Abt 1327–17 April 1365":"umbes 1327–17. aprill 1365","1327–1365":"1327–1365","1320–1389":"1320–1389","1360–1455":"1360–1455","–1370":"–1370","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","Abt 1327":"umbes 1327","1290":"1290","17 April 1365":"17. aprill 1365","1327":"1327","1345":"1345","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","Aft 1360":"pärast 1360","after 10 January 1363":"pärast 10. jaanuari 1363","Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland":"Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland","Lovat Castle, Beauly, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1327–17 April 1365":"noin 1327–17. huhtikuuta 1365","1327–1365":"1327–1365","1320–1389":"1320–1389","1360–1455":"1360–1455","–1370":"–1370","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1292–Female":"1292–Kuollut","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","Abt 1327":"noin 1327","1290":"1290","17 April 1365":"17. huhtikuuta 1365","1327":"1327","1345":"1345","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","Aft 1360":"1360 jälkeen","after 10 January 1363":"10. tammikuuta 1363 jälkeen","Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland":"Macduff, Banffshire, Scotland","Lovat Castle, Beauly, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland"},"fr":{"Abt 1327–17 April 1365":"environ 1327–17 avril 1365","1327–